            <p>THE HEBREW STANDARD.<lb/>
                HEBREW STANDARD CO.		NO. 338 BROADWAY.	JOB PRINTING OF EVERY<lb/>
                PUBLISHERS.		J. P. SOLOMON&#44; EDITOR.		DESCRIPTION.<lb/>
                New York&#44; Aug 12 1886<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I have given the printer your additions<lb/> &#38; they will be attended to.<lb/></p>
            <p>Whenever your time will permit I would be thankful for<lb/> some short poems in Hebrew &#38; if I can obtain from various<lb/> sources a sufficient number I will stereotype after each issue<lb/> with a view to their future publication.<lb/></p>
            <p>The only obstacle that stares me in the face is the difficulty of<lb/> obtaining &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#38; I am afraid that your lines will be shorn<lb/> of them&#44; which I hope will not cause any deterioration of their worth.<lb/></p>
            <p>The German &#38; Polish Congregation of Montreal enquired as to the most<lb/> suitable Rabbi to deliver an address at their proposed dedication.  I took the<lb/> liberty of suggesting your name as my beau&#91;&#63;&#93; ideal of a Jewish minister.<lb/>  I am afraid that the summer silence &#91;&#63;&#93; the Seminary will show<lb/> a lack of spirit in the good cause&#44; for I am a firm believer in aggressive<lb/> agitation<lb/>  Respy yours<lb/> J. P. Solomon.<lb/></p>
            </body>
